## Introduction

In this part, we will use lasso regression to train a prediction model. The dependent variables here are LVs extracted from [pwy-plier-nochrx](https://xsun1229.github.io/pathway_analysis/pwy-plier-nochrx.html) and the independent variables are genotype of certain variants. (LVs ~ variant genotype)


## Material and Methods

1. We used whole blood gene expression data from GTEx including 670 samples. In genptype data, there are 10,403,249 variants in total (variants in chrX have been excluded). 
2. Performed association test between the 128 LVs and all SNPs using Plink. We corrected the results for genotype PCs (We used Plink to compute 10 PCs and used them as corvariates in association test).
3. From 2, we selected all SNPs with p < 1E-02. For each LV, we can get a set of around 100,000 variants.
4. Trained Lasso/Elastic net using these SNPs on the training data(80% of the samples) and evaluated the performance in the testing data(20% of the samples).

##Results

### Heritability vs R-squared

This figure shows the prediction performance (R2 of Lasso/Elastic_net regression on training set in red) in comparison to LV heritability estimates (black; standard errors in gray). Performance was assessed using tenfold cross-validation in the GTEx whole-blood cohort (on training set, n = 536) with the elastic net and lasso models.

### Debugging

There seems to be some overfitting problems. So I did some debuggings. 

#### Table
The table below shows the heritability of LVs and performance of the training models. The table has been sorted by Heritability from small to large.

Some notations to explain: rsq_min is the r-squared when lambda=lambda.min,  ncoef_nzero_min is the number of non-zero coefficients when lambda=lambda.min, mspe_min is mean squared prediction error when lambda=lambda.min (mean squared error on test set). When the suffix is '_1se', the notations mean lambda=lambda.1se. Suffix '_l' means lasso regression and '_e' means elastic_net

Some LVs like LV5,LV8 have pretty low heritability but have very high r-squared. In such LVs, the training model always selected many variants(ncoef_nzero). 
Other LVs like LV101,LV113 have relatively high heritability but very low r-squared.In such LVs, the training model always selected few variants(ncoef_nzero). 

It seems that the r-squared issue is a variante selection issue?
